• Short answer: yes and no.

  It is not mainly a “smart fallback coercion” system for those block/logo glyphs. For the ranges you’re noticing,
  mintty often bypasses font glyphs and draws them itself so cells connect cleanly.

  Key evidence from this repo:

  - In output processing, those chars are marked for special rendering (FONTFAM=11):
      - src/termout.c:5515
      - src/termout.c:5521
  - That includes:
      - Box Drawing U+2500..U+257F (when BoxDrawing is on)
      - Block Elements U+2580..U+259F (always in this path)
      - Powerline private-use symbols U+E0B0..U+E0BF (except two)
  - Renderer treats this as self-drawn graphics (boxpower) instead of normal font text:
      - src/wintext.c:3114
      - src/wintext.c:4083
  - Concrete block-element drawing code (rectangles/shades, etc.):
      - src/wintext.c:4502
      - src/wintext.c:4504

  Docs explicitly confirm this design:

  - docs/mintty.1:1978 says BoxDrawing enables self-drawn box graphics for unbroken connections.
  - wiki/Tips.md:1045 says mintty draws box-drawing characters itself for seamless rendering.

  So for a logo like ▐▛███▜▌, the “almost perfect/no gaps” behavior is primarily from mintty’s special self-draw
  path (plus zoom/full-cell handling), not from ordinary fallback font matching. Normal Windows fallback/font
  linking still exists for other characters, but this specific effect is mostly deliberate custom rendering.


